520	20	https://www.darkreading.com/cyberattacks-data-breaches/iranian-state-apt-telcos-satellite-companies	Iranian State APT Blitzes Telcos & Satellite Companies	2025-09-19 13:59:31	\N	["Nate Nelson, Contributing Writer"]	[]	A Charming Kitten subgroup is performing some of the most bespoke cyberattacks ever witnessed in the wild, to down select high-value targets.	Nate Nelson, Contributing Writer September 19, 2025 Source: Arterra Picture Library via Alamy Stock Photo In the span of just a couple of weeks, Iranian hackers have stolen highly sensitive data from 11 global telecommunications companies, satellite operators, and aerospace equipment manufacturers. Cyber defenders have been tracking or otherwise fending off Middle Eastern cyberattacks by "Subtle Snail" (aka UNC1549) for around four years now. First, in 2021, it attacked a Bahrain-based IT integrator perhaps, researchers thought, as a window to its more valuable clients. Later, it seemed to have developed a focus on aerospace and defense firms. Google researchers observed attacks in Israel and the United Arab Emirates (UAE) , and evidence of further activity in Albania, India, and Turkey. In a burst of recent attacks observed by researchers at Prodaft, Subtle Snail spread its operations across the Middle East, Europe, and North America . Besides aerospace and defense, a lot of its focus has been in the telecommunications industry, particularly satellite communications . A few of its latest victims have been massive companies serving millions of customers big catches they managed to pull off by customizing every single attack to the nines. Charming Kitten Spies on Telcos Subtle Snail's success can be attributed to the significant amount of effort it puts into customizing its attacks for each and every victim. First, the group identifies key personnel in the organization it's interested in. IT administrators, researchers, and developers make for ideal pickings, for their having greater-than-average access to sensitive systems and business data. The attackers do background research on these folks, reviewing their online profiles particularly LinkedIn and whatever other useful information they might have published on the Web. They also, of course, gather what they can about the target's employer. Next the attackers don the disguise of a recruiter on LinkedIn and reach out to their targets with fake job openings. These fake profiles, openings, and the phishing domains they connect to are all designed to impersonate either Telespazio or Safran Group, European companies in the outer space and aerospace technology sectors. Targets are attracted to the job openings that seem perfect for their career trajectories What a coincidence! so they follow the phishing links and start divulging their personal information. The backdoor they end up contracting, "MiniBike," is even more customized than the phishing lure they fell for. On its own, it's a fairly standard piece of badware: gathering basic system data, establishing persistence, connecting to a command-and-control (C2) server, and supporting a dozen more standard fare malicious functions. MiniBike's primary purpose is to load additional components in the form of dynamic link libraries (DLLs). In a kind of comical exaggeration of a modular backdoor, each potential function it can carry out must be downloaded in the form of its own DLL, slightly changed so as to constitute its own variant. So if MiniBike deploys a keylogger on two different systems, they won't look exactly the same. "Operationally, the malware is modular and its functionally the same," explains Halit Alptekin, chief intelligence officer at Prodaft. Still, in effect, "even a single-bit change produces a different hash, and many AV products struggle to detect those variants. Some vendors perform behavior analysis, but their detection rules are still not comprehensive enough to catch every variant." He adds, "We observe similar patterns across other Iran-nexus threat clusters. Initial access methods vary, but most campaigns still rely on DLL sideloading combined with custom malware that looks nearly identical." Subtle Snail: A Slime Trail of International Espionage At the conclusion of its attack chain, Subtle Snail aims to steal a variety of data, including but not limited to: System and network information, including insights into installed security programs, virtual private network (VPN) configuration files, and data pertaining to the user's browser usage patterns Credentials stored in password managers, files, Chromium browsers, and more Personally identifying information (PII) in the form of photographs, passport scans, or wherever else such sensitive data might be found on a targeted system Proprietary business data, in whatever form it might come in confidential documents, customer databases, and source code repositories The goal, overall, appears to be twofold: gathering information useful for research and development, and snatching call data records (CDR) for use in international espionage. This tracks with what we know of Subtle Snail in general. The group is linked to Tortoiseshell (aka Unyielding Wasp), which in turn is believed to be part of Charming Kitten one of those umbrella advanced persistent threats (APTs), like North Korea's Kimsuky , that seems to catch blame for any and all attacks from its host country. Charming Kitten is associated with Iran's Revolutionary Guard Corps' (IRGC). Attribution is always a challenge, Alpetkin warns. What he can say with relative certainty is that Iran's hackers are split into distinct roles malware developers and initial access operators and that "many of those individuals are employed by security companies while also working for government customers." And Subtle Snail, by all accounts, is operating on behalf of state interests. He points out that "if documents are stolen from a telecom, the government is often the only available buyer for that type of data." About the Author Nate Nelson, Contributing Writer Nate Nelson is a writer based in New York City. He formerly worked as a reporter at Threatpost, and wrote "Malicious Life," an award-winning Top 20 tech podcast on Apple and Spotify. Outside of Dark Reading, he also co-hosts "The Industrial Security Podcast." See more from Nate Nelson, Contributing Writer You May Also Like	2c88d44cdaf3e5859b4ab77ef1201bc62538ea9e47f56d49d3a1dcb2d7aa6564	{"feed_entry": {"id": "https://www.darkreading.com/cyberattacks-data-breaches/iranian-state-apt-telcos-satellite-companies", "link": "https://www.darkreading.com/cyberattacks-data-breaches/iranian-state-apt-telcos-satellite-companies", "published": "Fri, 19 Sep 2025 13:59:31 GMT", "updated": "Fri, 19 Sep 2025 13:59:31 GMT"}, "extraction_method": "rss_with_modern_fallback", "content_type": "article", "word_count": 919, "content_length": 5993, "processing_timestamp": "2025-09-29T05:07:46.955688", "publication_day_of_week": "Friday", "publication_month": "September", "publication_year": 2025, "age_days": 9, "threat_keywords": ["malware", "phishing", "apt", "attack", "campaign", "threat", "security", "backdoor"], "threat_keyword_count": 8, "threat_hunting_score": 10.5, "perfect_keyword_matches": [], "good_keyword_matches": ["Detection", "network"], "lolbas_matches": [], "intelligence_matches": ["APT", "attribution", "observed", "victim", "targeted", "espionage"], "negative_matches": [], "processed_at": "2025-09-29T05:07:46.971404"}	92788863326306942	14	2025-09-29 05:07:47.448521	pending	0	2025-09-29 05:07:47.451426	2025-09-29 05:07:47.451427
521	20	https://www.darkreading.com/cyber-risk/7-lessons-securing-ai-transformation-former-cia-digital-guru	7 Lessons for Securing AI Transformation From Digital Guru Jennifer Ewbank	2025-09-18 22:31:43	\N	["Ericka Chickowski, Contributing Writer"]	[]	The former CIA deputy director for digital innovation discusses resilience, cultural shifts, and cyber fundamentals in the AI era.	Ericka Chickowski, Contributing Writer September 18, 2025 Source: Kiyoshi Takahase Segundo via alamy stock photo The road to AI failures is paved with good intentions and dodgy deployments. Many people are working overtime to lay down those bricks as organizations hurry to maintain relevance in an era of AI transformation. CISOs and business risk executives alike are tasked with helping their executives grapple with a difficult balancing act. They've got to weigh the risks of building insecure or resilient artificial intelligence (AI) against the risk of failing to move fast enough. Security teams themselves are also under increasing pressure to transform their own operations with the deep analytics and generative power of AI even more securely and resiliently than many enterprise applications. Jennifer Ewbank is intimately familiar with this tall task. As the former deputy director of the CIA for Digital innovation, Ewbank headed up the agency's AI-driven digital transformation starting in 2019. The work required tremendous organizational change and demanded that the CIA rethink cybersecurity. Ewbank helped guide the CIA in updating and centralizing its data management and analytic strategies, rolling out the world's most sophisticated GenAI-driven intelligence platforms before generative AI was even a thing in the commercial world, and driving real-time analysis of unspeakable troves of data. Dark Reading recently spoke to Ewbank who retired in 2024 to embark on a career in consulting to get her thoughts on lessons that CISOs can learn from her CIA transformation journey. Debriefing on the CIA's AI Transformation When Ewbank took on her role, the CIA was at a crossroads. GenAI hadn't captured the mainstream mindshare, but higher-ups at the spy agency could see the writing on the wall. At the same time, the agency was drowning in data and needed to rapidly scale up analysis to handle the deluge. "The job of recruiting spies and collecting intelligence has become devastatingly challenging in the digital era," Ewbank says. Everything intelligence officers do their movements and who they talk to when recruiting assets or collecting secret intelligence is tracked, she explains. "All of that potentially is sensed. It's recorded by something somewhere," she says. "So you can kind of see the scope of the challenge there." If the agency was going to get value from that data, it needed to be able to sift through all of the signals from a rapidly increasing number of sources in near real time. "My view very early on was we had to get AI right," Ewbank says. "We would fail as an organization and become obsolete in short order and the bad guys would win if we did not." To get AI right, the CIA needed better cooperation in coordinating the digital infrastructure and intelligence across what was a very siloed set of different tech domains. It was countering advanced attacks, and leadership understood implicitly that the AI advances it made needed to be cyber-resilient from the start. This led to the formation of the Directorate of Digital Innovation (DDI), for which Ewbank was selected to run. The 7 Lessons for CISOs While the CIA is unlike any organization in the private sector, many of the challenges and breakthroughs made by Ewbank's team should be as relatable to commercial entities as they are to the spy world. The agency had to grind its way through the friction of culture change, deal with the realities of technical debt, and address skills gaps. It also had to find a way to embed security in every step of its work. Lesson 1: Organizational Culture Is Key Early on, the biggest AI challenges had nothing to do with tech know-how, Ewbank says. Even with the most amazing technologists on board, organizations can fall apart if all those rock stars aren't collaborating tightly and with the business leadership laser-focused on a business goal. "It became very clear that technology wasn't the biggest challenge; it was organizational, Ewbank says. Before the digital directorate was formed, the CIA didn't have the "muscle memory" to pull off a truly transformative tech initiative. The technical silos, the budgets, and the way personnel were allotted were "quite rigid," she says. "It really became an exercise in trying to align organizations to work horizontally and to break some of the cultural rigidity that was in place, not due to animus or ill will, but simply because that's how organizations evolve over time," Ewbank says. In that respect, she was leadership's ace in the hole for this effort. Rather than bringing in a tech insider, they tapped into her leadership skills in the CIA's operational world. Ewbank had previously spent decades in the field, serving in many different leadership positions around the globe, including four stints as chief of station. "I came out of the world of espionage to lead digital tech, and that was an intentional choice on the part of our director to bring alignment to the hardest parts of our mission, to understand our adversaries, understand their capabilities, and overlay that on our plans to drive more urgent tech adaptation at the agency," she says. Lesson 2: When AI Drives the Mission, It Better Be Trustworthy One of the most transformative parts of Ewbank's digital innovation work was helping the CIA rethink where cybersecurity was placed within the organization. It had previously been positioned in the Office of Security, but she lobbied to pull the CISO role under her directorate's leadership to change the mindset to have cybersecurity completely baked into digital capabilities. This was crucial because the CISO needed to be involved in the discussions at every step of the way to drive innovation in cyber threat intelligence and ensure the AI capabilities built to analyze it all were safe and reliable. Building a brain trust comprised of the CISO, CIO, and chief data officer made it easier to make rapid, risk-aware decisions. "Our digital C-suite was a big stepping stone," she says. "The CISO was now at the table when systems and programs were being discussed and designed and not brought in at the end," she says. Private-sector leaders should take this lesson to heart and bake cybersecurity into the fabric of AI technology deployments, Ewbank says. The damage potential is great when adversaries exploit AI, she says. "I worry about the future of organizations and their AI systems that are being rapidly deployed without cybersecurity guardrails in place. I worry about the outcomes when cybersecurity is not sitting at the table as teams put together new capabilities," she says. "They shouldn't move without security." Lesson 3: Intentional Education Tracks Can Bridge Tech Culture Silos One of the most effective methods of busting tech culture silos was using education to help technologists start talking the same language, Ewbank says. As part of her transformation push, she mandated that everyone in her directorate take classes to become certified in cross-domain digital acumen. A Ph.D. data scientist may never think about network design, data transport, cloud computing or how cybersecurity thinks about those issues, Ewbank explains. Her team built a "digital university," or a curriculum that taught thousands of technologists in different specialties foundational knowledge about how everything worked cohesively. "It didn't make everyone an expert in everything, but it helped everyone have a common lexicon across the entire digital tech stack," she says. This kind of intentional, structured learning can help cybersecurity and other tech leaders bridge culture gaps and foster more collaborative environments. This has always been important but will be even more so in the AI era. "My hypothesis with the future of cybersecurity and AI is that we're really going to need security people with deep data expertise," she says. "And in the AI data world, we're really going to have to have people understand cybersecurity enough that they can bake this in from the beginning because we're seeing all sorts of potential vulnerabilities out there." Lesson 4: Security Doesn't Own the Risk Getting all of the technologists on the same page is crucial for managing AI's cyber-risks, but equally important is keeping executives fully apprised of their cyber-risk variables. One of Ewbank's big goals during the transformation was to keep the upper echelon of CIA leadership advised of the risk and firmly rooted in the reality of who truly owns it. "We made a concerted effort to bring the entire CIA leadership team in to understand that cyber-risk is their risk. It's not the CISO's risk," she says. "The CISO is going to have great ideas, technical acumen, team tools, telemetry, and all that kind of stuff. But the business decisions reside with people who own the risk." This lesson holds just as much water in the private sector, where risk is a board and executive team issue. "It's the CISO's job to advise, but it is the CEO, the CFO, the chief risk officer, and others who have to decide, 'Are we willing to take this risk or that risk? Are we willing to spend money to buy down this risk or not?'" Ewbank says. Lesson 5: AI Resilience Rests in Boring Fundamentals As her cross-functional team dug into the real work of AI transformation, they found that a significant part of that work rested in the most boring of tech and cyber fundamentals. "It wasn't flashy," Ewbank says, but it meant modernizing processes and getting data, governance and ethical frameworks right. "That's the boring stuff that nobody wanted to spend time and money on, but you have to do that in order to make capabilities available, whether in cybersecurity or in intelligence operations or analysis," she says. "Everyone needed that. But nobody wanted to invest in it." From a cybersecurity resilience perspective, this meant focusing on the tech and governance around identity management and access controls, ensuring entitlements and architecture were designed to limit damage in the event of unauthorized access. "It's not fun or sexy, but you've got to get it right or AI risks will just continue to increase," she says. "That is something every company [that] is moving headlong to bring in new AI needs to do. They need to take a breath and figure out how they're going to get the data, how they're going to deploy the cyber controls, and how they're going to determine whether an adversary is attempting to manipulate their systems." Ewbank emphasizes that companies moving rapidly toward AI transformation need to take the time to frame their cyber-risks using adversarial thinking. It's an increasingly necessary skill. "You can have all the telemetry in the world, and you can have all the controls in the world, and if you aren't actually thinking about what your adversary can do and what they want to do, you're missing a piece of the puzzle," she says. Making AI resilient will require an approach that looks beyond vulnerabilities and considers intent. This means engaging in not just simple threat modeling exercises but role-playing or table-top exercises that consider what a malicious actor will want to accomplish when entering the AI model and working backward into the tech. "Role-play as the adversary to look at your systems as an external actor would," she says. "Fusing automation and human analysis with a better understanding of adversarial intent unlocks a new way of thinking that is necessary in this new cyber landscape." Lesson 7: Choose Imperfection Over Inaction The final lesson for CISOs ties to the one about owning risk and understanding the advisory role that cybersecurity leadership plays in an AI transformation: Companies should most definitely be trying to manage cyber-risk along the journey, but they can't let security analysis paralysis keep them from moving forward. "You're never going to have enough information to make a decision and yet you have to make a decision and you have to move," Ewbank says. The CISO's job will be to help leaders think about AI resilience at each step of the transformation, with the understanding that everyone involved also needs to weigh the risk of not taking action. "You want perfect insight because you don't want to take measures that might degrade a system, and you don't want to do something that might harm your company's operations, she says. "But there is so much risk in inaction, too. At the CIA, we understood that doing nothing is sometimes the biggest risk of all." Read more about: CISO Corner About the Author Ericka Chickowski, Contributing Writer Ericka Chickowski specializes in coverage of information technology and business innovation. She has focused on information security for the better part of a decade and regularly writes about the security industry as a contributor to Dark Reading. See more from Ericka Chickowski, Contributing Writer You May Also Like	87618d5518bf39c76573b97b2a43ff913925ef3c1378a8ac1b07d51b121ced73	{"feed_entry": {"id": "https://www.darkreading.com/cyber-risk/7-lessons-securing-ai-transformation-former-cia-digital-guru", "link": "https://www.darkreading.com/cyber-risk/7-lessons-securing-ai-transformation-former-cia-digital-guru", "published": "Thu, 18 Sep 2025 22:31:43 GMT", "updated": "Thu, 18 Sep 2025 22:31:43 GMT"}, "extraction_method": "rss_with_modern_fallback", "content_type": "article", "word_count": 2107, "content_length": 12911, "processing_timestamp": "2025-09-29T05:07:46.978086", "publication_day_of_week": "Thursday", "publication_month": "September", "publication_year": 2025, "age_days": 10, "threat_keywords": ["apt", "attack", "exploit", "threat", "security"], "threat_keyword_count": 5, "threat_hunting_score": 2.2, "perfect_keyword_matches": [], "good_keyword_matches": ["cloud", "network"], "lolbas_matches": [], "intelligence_matches": ["espionage"], "negative_matches": ["read more", "fundamentals"], "processed_at": "2025-09-29T05:07:47.011834"}	18435950744790924348	12	2025-09-29 05:07:47.453021	pending	0	2025-09-29 05:07:47.457202	2025-09-29 05:07:47.457203
522	20	https://www.darkreading.com/cyber-risk/tiktok-deal-enterprise-risks	TikTok Deal Won't End Enterprise Risks	2025-09-18 20:28:19	\N	["Jai Vijayan, Contributing Writer"]	[]	The proposed restructuring plan would address many concerns related to the social media platform, but risks remain for security teams.	Jai Vijayan, Contributing Writer September 18, 2025 Source: Tada Images via Shutterstock With a deal about the future of TikTok in the US beginning to take shape, the question for cybersecurity professionals now is how and to what extent changes to the company's structure will alter its risk profile. The Wall Street Journal and other media outlets this week reported on US and Chinese negotiators working on a plan that would give a consortium of US technology companies, venture capital firms, and private equity investors ownership of around 80% of TikTok's US operations. The consortium will include Oracle, which currently already hosts and manages TikTok's US user data, venture capital firm Andreessen Horowitz, and private equity firm Silver Lake. New US-Based Entity The deal calls for a new US-based entity with a majority US board which will include one government-designated member to operate TikTok in the country. It is largely similar to a deal presented to the Trump Administration in April just before the tariff war with China started. The goal is to find a way to allow TikTok to operate in the US in a manner that addresses deep and widespread concern over the social media giant's data management practices and its potential for spreading misinformation. China-based ByteDance, which owns TikTok, is beholden, like all Chinese companies, to provide data to the Chinese government when ordered under the country's national security laws. Many perceive this as presenting a major data privacy and security risk for the 170 million or so US users of the social media platform, and to organizations where employees might be using TikTok on work devices. In April 2024, then President Joe Biden signed a law that required ByteDance to sell its ownership in TikTok to a US company within a year or face a total ban in the country . When the US Supreme Court upheld the ban in January 2025, TikTok briefly went dark in the US before restoring service after President Trump signed an executive order that offered a temporary reprieve. Wide Concerns Concerns over TikTok's data handling practices and its obligations to the Chinese government are not unique to the US. Earlier this year, the Irish Data Protection Commission (DPC) slapped a 530 million fine on TikTok over alleged violations of the EU's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) in relation to the company's handling of protected data. In 2023, the European Commission and Council of the EU banned government employees and contractors from using TikTok over data security fears. Canada too has banned TikTok from government devices and last November ordered TikTok's Canadian subsidiary to be shuttered . The question now is how far the proposed deal for TikTok's US operations will go in alleviating these concerns. If the proposal goes through as presently structured, it would address the major issue of where TikTok stores its US data and who controls it, says Adam Marr , chief information security officer (CISO) at Arctic Wolf. "Moving US operations under majority US ownership, with Oracle managing data in Texas, would reduce the risk of direct foreign state access," Marr says. "But ownership and geography alone are not enough to make a platform safe. Transparency, accountability, and ongoing oversight matter just as much." A Step in the Right Direction From a cybersecurity and data privacy standpoint, the proposed deal could give consumers more confidence that their personal data isn't flowing directly overseas. For businesses, though, the risk profile doesn t change much, Marr says. "TikTok is still a highly data-intensive application, and that means any employee using it on a company device or network could introduce risk." Organizations cannot afford to assume that TikTok is safe once any restructuring is complete. The app will still collect a significant amount of device and behavioral data, Marr says. "That information can be misused, and the biggest enterprise risk continues to be social engineering and data leakage through employee activity." Lily Li, founder of Metaverse Law, points out that storing TikTok data in Oracle-owned facilities in Texas would immunize it against China's cybersecurity laws. The Chinese government would not be able to ask Oracle to decrypt and provide data from these facilities. "The ultimate structure and organization of this US entity is still up in the air," Li says. However, there's a need for transparency about the people who will have administrative access to Oracle's production systems and data. "To prevent enterprise data leaks abroad or espionage by foreign actors, the individuals who maintain the administrative access, controls, and encryption keys should be US individuals who report to management in the US," Li says. It's important to keep in mind also that additional controls by themselves are not enough, because TikTok still will be a publicly available social media platform. "Organizations that maintain sensitive information, including the identity and location of military and government assets, should still have policies in place prohibiting the disclosure of such information on social media," Li says. In addition, if individuals are not careful about how or when they post, they could still inadvertently share sensitive geolocation or device data based on their interactions with TikTok, the TikTok pixel, and other trackers, she warns. The Recommendation Algorithm Issue There's also the issue of TikTok's content recommendation algorithms. According to The Wall Street Journal, TikTok engineers are recreating a set of such algorithms for the US version of the app, using technology licensed from ByteDance. "This is the part that's hardest to solve," Marr says. Algorithms shape what people see and believe, and if the code is still licensed from ByteDance without full transparency, it's likely that concerns about hidden data collection or influence operations will remain unaddressed. "The influence angle may be as important as the privacy one. We need to recognize that security isn't just about where the data sits it's also about how the platform shapes behavior and discourse." Satish Swargam, principal security consultant at Black Duck, says the TikTok recommendation algorithms that the US operation will license from ByteDance need to be carefully evaluated for data leaks and the potential for influence operations. "Oracle and other US-based companies are not new to such deals," he says, pointing to Oracle's $28.3 billion purchase of healthcare giant Cerner as an example. Even so, caution is warranted with the TikTok deal. "There is potential for non-US-based algorithms to extract user data and influence campaigns in the US," Swargam says. "The TikTok deal calls for tighter security controls, comprehensive security analysis of all software artifacts involved and a deep dive threat model." Read more about: CISO Corner About the Author Jai Vijayan, Contributing Writer Jai Vijayan is a seasoned technology reporter with over 20 years of experience in IT trade journalism. He was most recently a Senior Editor at Computerworld, where he covered information security and data privacy issues for the publication. Over the course of his 20-year career at Computerworld, Jai also covered a variety of other technology topics, including big data, Hadoop, Internet of Things, e-voting, and data analytics. Prior to Computerworld, Jai covered technology issues for The Economic Times in Bangalore, India. Jai has a Master's degree in Statistics and lives in Naperville, Ill. See more from Jai Vijayan, Contributing Writer You May Also Like	303d24e3b0078627706168a093b24064c9ba90ca4bcb2b021adc2b0d3bf39066	{"feed_entry": {"id": "https://www.darkreading.com/cyber-risk/tiktok-deal-enterprise-risks", "link": "https://www.darkreading.com/cyber-risk/tiktok-deal-enterprise-risks", "published": "Thu, 18 Sep 2025 20:28:19 GMT", "updated": "Thu, 18 Sep 2025 20:28:19 GMT"}, "extraction_method": "rss_with_modern_fallback", "content_type": "article", "word_count": 1204, "content_length": 7636, "processing_timestamp": "2025-09-29T05:07:47.018812", "publication_day_of_week": "Thursday", "publication_month": "September", "publication_year": 2025, "age_days": 10, "threat_keywords": ["campaign", "threat", "security"], "threat_keyword_count": 3, "threat_hunting_score": 1.2, "perfect_keyword_matches": [], "good_keyword_matches": ["network"], "lolbas_matches": [], "intelligence_matches": ["espionage"], "negative_matches": ["statistics", "read more"], "processed_at": "2025-09-29T05:07:47.038635"}	889045093253391097	9	2025-09-29 05:07:47.458903	pending	0	2025-09-29 05:07:47.461844	2025-09-29 05:07:47.461844
523	20	https://www.darkreading.com/cyberattacks-data-breaches/sonicwall-breached-firewall-backup	SonicWall Breached, Firewall Backup Data Exposed	2025-09-18 19:26:36	\N	["Alexander Culafi"]	[]	Threat actors breached the MySonicWall service and accessed backup firewall configuration files belonging to "fewer than 5%" of its install base, according to the company.	Alexander Culafi , Senior News Writer , Dark Reading September 18, 2025 Source: Perov Stanislav via Alamy Stock Photo Security vendor SonicWall suffered a data breach that exposed customer firewall configuration file backups. On Sept. 17, SonicWall , a vendor best known for its network security appliances, published a knowledge base article disclosing what it described as a "cloud backup file incident." The company said its security teams recently detected "suspicious activity targeting the cloud backup service for firewalls" and confirmed it to be a security event in the past few days. Unidentified threat actors accessed backup firewall preference files stored in the cloud representing "fewer than 5% of our firewall install base," according to SonicWall. Attackers were able to access encrypted credentials as well as firewall configuration files "that could make it easier for attackers to potentially exploit the related firewall." "We are not presently aware of these files being leaked online by threat actors," SonicWall said in its disclosure . "This was not a ransomware or similar event for SonicWall, rather this was a series of brute force attacks aimed at gaining access to the preference files stored in backup for potential further use by threat actors." What to About the SonicWall Breach SonicWall firewall customers with preference files backed up in MySonicWall.com are considered impacted by the incident. SonicWall advises customers to log in to their MySonicWall account, verify whether cloud backups are enabled (those with disabled backups are not at risk), and verify if impacted serial numbers are listed in their account. For impacted customers, SonicWall created a dedicated containment, remediation, and monitoring guide . In large part, the recommendations involve limiting the potential for compromise and, more importantly, rotating all password and MFA credentials saved in the firewall. For customers that have used the cloud backup feature but don't have serial numbers listed in their MySonicWall account, the vendor intends to provide additional guidance to determine potential impact to its advisory in the coming days. Dark Reading contacted SonicWall for additional details about the breach. A spokesperson for the vendor says attackers accessed "the API service for cloud backup." In addition, the spokesperson adds there is no evidence threat actors leveraged exposed data against impacted customers in attacks at this time. SonicWall also shared a statement with Dark Reading. "As soon as we discovered the activity, SonicWall immediately disabled access to the backup feature, implemented infrastructure and process changes to further secure our systems, and launched a comprehensive review of potentially affected environments. We also enlisted the services of a leading third-party IR and Consulting Firm to validate our investigation and findings. Impacted customers and partners have been directly notified with clear instructions to secure their devices," the statement reads. The statement advises customers to check the aforementioned knowledge base article, as new information will be added there first. "We are committed to full transparency and will continue to share updates as our investigation progresses." SonicWall's Recent Security History The breach marks the latest security issue for SonicWall, which has become a popular target for a variety of threat actors that have increasingly shifted toward attacking vulnerable edge devices . Though unrelated, the MySonicWall incident follows an advisory SonicWall made last month concerning a wave of attacks targeting Gen 7 and newer SonicWall firewalls with SSLVPN enabled. Specifically, Akira ransomware actors are exploiting improper access control vulnerability CVE-2024-40766 in a new campaign. SonicWall said it was investigating fewer than 40 incidents, and recommended customers update to the latest firmware, reset all local user account passwords for any accounts with SSLVPN access, and continue applying best practices. In May, CISA warned two SonicWall SMA vulnerabilities were under active exploitation. Thankfully, SonicWall patched the issues quickly , as exploiting the flaws could lead to root RCE attacks. About the Author Alexander Culafi Senior News Writer, Dark Reading Alex is a writer, journalist, and podcaster based in Boston. See more from Alexander Culafi You May Also Like	53221f87d8de07baf559776023df1a7e9501b90ca6c5a038c165c6c10996e711	{"feed_entry": {"id": "https://www.darkreading.com/cyberattacks-data-breaches/sonicwall-breached-firewall-backup", "link": "https://www.darkreading.com/cyberattacks-data-breaches/sonicwall-breached-firewall-backup", "published": "Thu, 18 Sep 2025 19:26:36 GMT", "updated": "Thu, 18 Sep 2025 19:26:36 GMT"}, "extraction_method": "rss_with_modern_fallback", "content_type": "article", "word_count": 659, "content_length": 4417, "processing_timestamp": "2025-09-29T05:07:47.043125", "publication_day_of_week": "Thursday", "publication_month": "September", "publication_year": 2025, "age_days": 10, "threat_keywords": ["ransomware", "attack", "vulnerability", "exploit", "breach", "campaign", "threat", "security", "incident"], "threat_keyword_count": 9, "threat_hunting_score": 9.7, "perfect_keyword_matches": [], "good_keyword_matches": ["Monitor", "cloud", "network"], "lolbas_matches": [], "intelligence_matches": ["campaign", "incident", "breach", "compromise", "discovered", "ransomware", "data breach"], "negative_matches": ["best practices"], "processed_at": "2025-09-29T05:07:47.054458"}	1249691842707386154	10	2025-09-29 05:07:47.46336	pending	0	