524	20	https://www.darkreading.com/vulnerabilities-threats/mastering-digital-breadcrumbs-stay-ahead-of-evolving-threats	Mastering Digital Breadcrumbs to Stay Ahead of Evolving Threats	2025-09-17 22:14:02	\N	["Richard Thurston"]	[]	Digital forensics offers a challenging but rewarding career path for cybersecurity professionals willing to invest in specialized knowledge and continuous learning.	Richard Thurston , Contributing Writer, Dark Reading September 17, 2025 Source: Peter Maszlen via Alamy Stock Photo Digital forensics is a fast-growing cybersecurity discipline in increasing demand by businesses. Professionals need special preparation and frequent upskilling, but the rewards can add up. It's a highly attractive area to work in, says Rob T. Lee, chief of research for SANS Institute. "It's very juicy and very sought after," says Lee, a former cyberspace warfare operations officer tasked to the National Security Agency. Forensics professionals pride themselves on not only investigating cybersecurity incidents, but uncovering often very obscure truths from the breadcrumbs of digital evidence. Their findings are critical in understanding and remediating incidents and learning from them. In some roles, they also provide evidence to support their organizations in legal action. They collect evidence, reconstruct attack paths, and analyze malware and tactics, techniques, and procedures (TTPs) used by threat actors. Practitioners work in hugely varying roles in both public and private sectors, including law enforcement. Many will find digital forensics/incident response (DF/IR) in their job descriptions or titles because most work closely with other critical cybersecurity functions, such as IR, threat hunting, and threat intelligence. "You need to be able to get answers quickly and with authority, and because of those pressures, it's a very important job," Lee says. "Organizations will invest heavily into having some of the best teams out there to be able to do this." Build Experience, Knowledge Digital forensics is no entry-level job: Practitioners must first acquire a solid, broad, and hands-on set of cybersecurity knowledge. Many training courses available from universities and private training providers help newcomers acquire base-level knowledge and set them up for more detailed learning. Beyond this, a strong knowledge of enterprise systems and architectures and threat actor TTPs will be required. The UK Cybersecurity Council has a tougher ask: knowledge of international and national statutory and regulatory requirements, compliance obligations, software security, security operations, and security ethics, as well as a focus on operational technology for roles in manufacturing companies or critical national infrastructure operators. Practitioners must also know a long list of scripting and common forensics tools. SANS Institute maps forensics skills in two groups: a crucial specialized role that requires knowledge of cloud and smartphone forensics, threat intelligence, and malware analysis, and a group of skills related to IR that includes host forensics (multiple operating systems) and network forensics, including a focus on addressing ransomware and other cyber extortion tactics. It suggests that practitioners learn the latter group first, but the division is misleading. The subject matter overlaps, and most practitioners will need a firm grounding in both groups of skills to grow. Career digital forensics investigator Brett Shavers has a different approach that is not purely technical. Cybersecurity professionals need five capabilities to work in DF/IR: a deep understanding of operating systems and file systems, log memory and timeline analysis, chain of custody awareness, critical thinking and evidence sequencing, and report writing that can survive cross-examination from an attorney. Forensics Titles, Responsibilities Vary Widely Once forensics professionals have their foot in the door, they carry a broad range of responsibilities. SANS Institute describes eight roles in forensics: forensics analyst, forensics investigator, malware analyst, media exploitation analyst, military operations/law enforcement agents, threat hunter, incident response, and SOC roles. In terms of remuneration, salaries are modest in the early stages. But highly specialized roles can pay extremely well when the professional has proved their knowledge and demonstrated outcomes due to the value it creates for the organization. Shavers urges practitioners to obtain that detailed knowledge, rather than growing a broad knowledge base. No one can master DF/IR across every technology, business arena, and network, he explains. "Let me murder the myth right now: DF/IR mastery isn't mastering the entire DF/IR field," he says. "The skill is knowing what to ask, where to look, what it means, and how to defend it. When you go deep, people come to you to solve problems. You're the trusted voice. The only path that matters is the one where you build skill, earn trust, and do the work right." Titles for forensics roles vary by company, and seniority is subject to HR strategies that can be confusing to outsiders. Bank of America has recently been recruiting a vice president or associate vice president, which may sound senior but is actually an expansion role for its DF/IR capabilities. Meanwhile, grocery retailer Tesco hired a DF/IR professional over the summer to work more broadly across its cybersecurity functions. Uber prefers the term "security investigator," which may sound junior but actually demands considerable experience and commands a high salary. The job will focus on response and forensics, as well as developing large-scale automation for incident response, increasing the maturity of incident response strategy, and mentoring junior security analysts. The fact that Uber wants experience beyond leading large threat hunts to include global crisis management capabilities is telling of the threats it faces and the business criticality of such a role. Develop Forensics Skills in New Technologies New technologies, such as artificial intelligence (AI), augmented reality (AR), and machine learning (ML), help and challenge forensic professionals. ML experts are quick to point to the way ML tools are making it easier not only for security teams, but also for threat actors. Forensic professionals will need to master these tools, which enable faster processing of evidence and faster results. They also need to understand how to defend AI assets, including infrastructure and models, which may contain significant intellectual property, an AR devices, such as smart glasses, then find compelling use cases in organizations. AI and synthetic media pose "unprecedented opportunities and complex challenges" for law enforcement and digital forensics professionals, says Yi Ma, professor at Hong Kong University's School of Computing and Data Science, which hosted Interpol's digital forensics conference in July. Professionals also need a strong understanding of mobile devices and deepfakes because these are frequently used to mislead organizations. And while connectivity in vehicles is limited at present, vehicle forensics is becoming an increasing area of focus, with demand likely to grow as the number of autonomous and connected vehicles increases. Consulting Means Fast Learning, Long Hours Careers in forensics don't follow a set path. Parveen Gill, a cybersecurity recruitment consultant for Barclay Simpson, urges professionals to consider working in consulting to gain a greater breadth of experience. "A good way is to go through the consultancy route because you are doing more cases per week," she says. Lee agrees with the merits of gaining a lot of experience working in top consulting firms, like CrowdStrike, Unit 42, or IBM X-Force. But on the flipside, he warns it could lead to long working hours. "You're put on planes a lot," he says. As professionals get older and want to settle down, he advises joining large enterprises, such as Fortune 500 companies. Professionals in forensics roles at smaller organizations could lose out on gaining experience, as they are dealing with fewer incidents, Lee explains. Moving across business verticals gives additional exposure to new forensic environments, he suggests. "If you're midcareer, you have a family and everything, I would recommend switching from your current role over into the forensics capacity and really look for good mentorship," he says. Lee also recommends taking part in "ranges" at industry events to keep their skills and knowledge up to date. Read more about: CISO Corner About the Author Richard Thurston Contributing Writer, Dark Reading Richard Thurston is a contributing writer for Dark Reading. See more from Richard Thurston You May Also Like	77c5ef4d1a17bbb550c86d2ca59b6e32c8da74ca5fed5fa258af48dcfccfb781	{"feed_entry": {"id": "https://www.darkreading.com/vulnerabilities-threats/mastering-digital-breadcrumbs-stay-ahead-of-evolving-threats", "link": "https://www.darkreading.com/vulnerabilities-threats/mastering-digital-breadcrumbs-stay-ahead-of-evolving-threats", "published": "Wed, 17 Sep 2025 22:14:02 GMT", "updated": "Wed, 17 Sep 2025 22:14:02 GMT"}, "extraction_method": "rss_with_modern_fallback", "content_type": "article", "word_count": 1259, "content_length": 8421, "processing_timestamp": "2025-09-29T05:07:47.059298", "publication_day_of_week": "Wednesday", "publication_month": "September", "publication_year": 2025, "age_days": 11, "threat_keywords": ["malware", "ransomware", "attack", "exploit", "threat", "security", "incident"], "threat_keyword_count": 7, "threat_hunting_score": 4.9, "perfect_keyword_matches": [], "good_keyword_matches": ["Hunting", "cloud", "network"], "lolbas_matches": [], "intelligence_matches": ["threat actor", "incident", "ransomware"], "negative_matches": ["how to", "read more", "training"], "processed_at": "2025-09-29T05:07:47.080767"}	15402941493214229465	9	2025-09-29 05