525	20	https://www.darkreading.com/cloud-security/cloud-edge-new-attack-surface	The Cloud Edge Is the New Attack Surface	2025-09-17 21:44:02	\N	["Robert Lemos, Contributing Writer"]	[]	The cloud now acts as the connecting infrastructure for many companies' assets from IoT devices to workstations to applications and workloads exposing the edge to threats.	Robert Lemos, Contributing Writer September 17, 2025 Source: rdonar via Shutterstock As companies expand their use of cloud computing beyond a few dozen applications to build the connective tissue between data centers and endpoints, their attack surface the cloud edge has grown. But securing that edge can be difficult. While security and operations teams are used to applying security at the edge of their own networks, the cloud edge is not always theirs to manage. Communications between cloud workloads often traverse the public Internet, putting data at risk of interception and opening up new holes in an organization's attack surface, experts say. Most companies do not have visibility into the Internet of Things (IoT) devices connected to their cloud services, the workloads spun up by every developer, or the service accounts and artificial intelligence (AI) agents that increasingly connect to services and hardware through the cloud, says John Qian, CISO at Aviatrix, a network security vendor. Users have to make sure that their connection from the edge to the cloud is secure and encrypted end-to-end not being decrypted before going to the cloud and that the edge devices are considered untrusted, he says. "You almost have to assume that attackers can break into those edge devices, and if they do break in, [you] have to ask, 'What sort of blast radius do they have coming into your cloud?'" Qian says. Traditionally, the network edge has been defined as an organization's infrastructure geographically and logically close to the end user. Increasingly, the infrastructure is cloud-based and not owned by the company meaning, the cloud edge. Companies have moved to secure access service edge (SASE), software-defined WANs, and zero-trust frameworks to help manage and secure the attack surface, but they have run into manageability and performance issues. Essentially, cloud services and infrastructure connect workstations, devices, workloads, and applications, allowing the distributed workforce to access the company's resources. But if they are not secure, attackers can compromise those resources , says Lawrence Pingree, a technical evangelist at Dispersive, a provider of zero-trust networking. "The entire network needs to have an extended trust layer from the cloud all the way to the edge locations, and we need to be able to deliver an isolated enclave in that location," he says. Going Private on Public Clouds Identity and endpoint protection are two key facets that form the foundation of security, says Aviatrix's Qian. However, much of the cloud edge relies only on usernames and passwords and, perhaps, two-factor authentication to protect assets. Additionally, many devices connected to or accessible from the cloud are lightweight and do not have the resources to run security agents . "You don't really have endpoint protection because you can put agents on certain endpoints, as some of the edge devices are very low-powered," Qian says. Low-powered devices often rely on lightweight encryption and lack built-in protection. "In those cases, network-layer control becomes critical," he adds. Aviatrix and Dispersive have both focused on microsegmentation to establish controls around collections of devices or around a single device and encryption to keep data and communications secure. This cloud-native security fabric (CSNF) allows for devices to communicate securely through the cloud and not be part of the organization's attack surface, Qian says. "We're looking at workload-to-workload and cloud-to-cloud communication and want to be able to enforce network policies when we do that," he says. Dispersive takes a similar approach, microsegmenting every workload and every service user from different edge device interactions and making devices uncontactable to nonauthenticated users what Pingree calls a "deflection cloud." "The average security company is using open source [code] for darn near everything they deliver," he says. You can't tell things like the type of cryptography used. You can't tell that it's even encrypted it looks like junk." Better Security, Better Performance In contrast, Pingree says Dispersive has built its own patented capabilities and can actually obfuscate the network. By rearchitecting how devices at the cloud edge communicate, the approach delivers better security, more control, and better performance, he says. On the performance side, the rapid move to AI workloads has changed traffic patterns, causing inefficiencies, Pingree says. "The problem is, when you start doing AI, you're uploading binaries, you're doing all of these highly interactive things, and what that means is it's changing the way that the traffic itself is represented on the network," he explains. "So you switch to SASE, and then you add AI, and all of these traffic patterns are basically completely reversing." In addition, the convergence of AI and quantum computing is a major future threat, capable of accelerating the discovery of zero-day vulnerabilities and breaking current encryption standards. Companies need to ensure the cloud edge does not become a wide-open attack surface, Pingree warns. "Imagine that AI and quantum can do these [promised attacks] with full automation and break [weak] cryptography on demand," he says. "You have to be prepared. It's not something that you can do after the fact." By combining microsegmentation and encryption on the network side with identity and endpoint protection, the cloud edge may finally be able to be trusted by users. About the Author Robert Lemos, Contributing Writer Veteran technology journalist of more than 20 years. Former research engineer. Written for more than two dozen publications, including CNET News.com, Dark Reading, MIT's Technology Review, Popular Science, and Wired News. Five awards for journalism, including Best Deadline Journalism (Online) in 2003 for coverage of the Blaster worm. Crunches numbers on various trends using Python and R. Recent reports include analyses of the shortage in cybersecurity workers and annual vulnerability trends. See more from Robert Lemos, Contributing Writer You May Also Like	507b49d7844ee4958ca305275927f553dab8500b46dd0b2e373fd0cf65cfe7ff	{"feed_entry": {"id": "https://www.darkreading.com/cloud-security/cloud-edge-new-attack-surface", "link": "https://www.darkreading.com/cloud-security/cloud-edge-new-attack-surface", "published": "Wed, 17 Sep 2025 21:44:02 GMT", "updated": "Wed, 17 Sep 2025 21:44:02 GMT"}, "extraction_method": "rss_with_modern_fallback", "content_type": "article", "word_count": 941, "content_length": 6154, "processing_timestamp": "2025-09-29T05:07:47.085962", "publication_day_of_week": "Wednesday", "publication_month": "September", "publication_year": 2025, "age_days": 11, "threat_keywords": ["attack", "vulnerability", "threat", "security", "zero-day"], "threat_keyword_count": 5, "threat_hunting_score": 5.5, "perfect_keyword_matches": [], "good_keyword_matches": ["cloud", "network"], "lolbas_matches": [], "intelligence_matches": ["compromise"], "negative_matches": [], "processed_at": "2025-09-29T05:07:47.102039"}	10803219635615591530	10	2025-09-29 05:07:47.471516	pending	0	2025-09-29 05:07:47.474131	2025-09-29 05:07:47.474131
526	20	https://www.darkreading.com/cyberattacks-data-breaches/scattered-lapsus-hunters-hacking-end	'Scattered Lapsus$ Hunters,' Others Announce End of Hacking Spree	2025-09-17 19:12:08	\N	["Kristina Beek"]	[]	Though the groups have shared their decision to go dark, threat researchers say there are signs that it's business as usual.	Kristina Beek , Associate Editor , Dark Reading September 17, 2025 Source: Stephen Dwyer via Alamy Stock Photo In what likely came as a shock to the cybersecurity community, several well-known threat actors and groups, including the newly formed 'Scattered Lapsus$ Hunters,' announced that they are shutting down their operations. The announcement was posted last week on the hacking marketplace BreachForums and Scattered Lapsus$ Hunters public Telegram channel via a farewell letter addressed the "World" at large. "Our objectives having been fulfilled, it is now time to say goodbye," read the letter . "We LAPSUS$, Trihash, Yurosh, yaxsh, WyTroZz, N3z0x, Nitroz, TOXIQUEROOT, Prosox, Pertinax, Kurosh, Clown, IntelBroker , Scattered Spider, Yukari, and among many others, have decided to go dark." Last month, members of Scattered Spider, Lapsus$ and ShinyHunters notorious cybercrime groups that researchers believe stem from "The Com" appeared to join forces under a new banner, "Scattered Lapsus$ Hunters," on a public Telegram channel. Members of the groups posted an exploit on the Telegram channel for two SAP NetWeaver Visual Composer vulnerabilities that were under attack in the wild. According to the letter, some of the members are planning to retire on the money that they had accumulated in their time with their respective group while others will continue in the field of cybersecurity in roles more beneficial to society, such as improving systems people rely on daily. Though the groups say they are shutting down, some of the messaging indicates there's more to the story. "Will Kering, Air France, American Airlines, British Airlines, and among many other critical infrastructure face THE CONSEQUENCES OF THEIR PUBLIC OR SECRET data breaches? I'd wonder too if I was them, as they know some have yet to receive any demand for ransom or anything else," it added. "Are their data currently being exploited, whilst US, UK, AU, and French authorities fill themselves with the illusions thinking they have gotten the situation under control?" The shutdown is more surprising for some groups compared to others, such as Scattered Spider, which has been on a rampage as of late despite the arrests of several alleged members . The cybercrime collective first gained notoriety with attacks on the Las Vegas casino and hotel giants Caesars Entertainment and MGM Resorts in 2023. The group, which is primarily made up of English-speaking teenagers and 20-somethings, went on to attack several British retailers, including Marks and Spencer, earlier this year, as well WestJet, Hawaiian Airlines, and other large corporations and their third-party IT providers. The group became a significant enough threat for the FBI to warn of their social engineering tactics this summer to groups that were more likely to be at risk. Other gangs, such as ShinyHunters, have been emulating some of Scattered Spider's tactics when attacking major enterprises such as Google, Louis Vuitton, Allianz, and more. What Comes Next for the Threat Groups? Security researchers are skeptical of the shutdown announcement, with some pointing to evidence of continued activity. In an updated blog post on Monday, researchers at Reliaquest said they've observed signs of Scattered Spider members targeting the financial sector, including "an increase in domains potentially linked to the group focusing on the finance sector, as well as a recently identified targeted intrusion against a US banking organization." Reliaquest initially reported last month that it believed the Scattered Spider hacking collective would soon shift their focus to the financial sector. This activity appears to have occurred after the group claimed to cease operations, indicating they may be operating under the guise of providing victims with a false sense of security, Reliaquest said. "Despite these claims, their TTPs and IoCs are still surfacing, showing that the threat remains active and evolving," the blog post said. "Staying vigilant and proactive is critical as these groups continue to adapt their methods." About the Author Kristina Beek Associate Editor, Dark Reading Skilled writer and editor covering cybersecurity for Dark Reading. See more from Kristina Beek You May Also Like	33742b7c4b8ae3f9f351d841ee6582ac75daf734b19fb1cec14b3ba0705b7f44	{"feed_entry": {"id": "https://www.darkreading.com/cyberattacks-data-breaches/scattered-lapsus-hunters-hacking-end", "link": "https://www.darkreading.com/cyberattacks-data-breaches/scattered-lapsus-hunters-hacking-end", "published": "Wed, 17 Sep 2025 19:12:08 GMT", "updated": "Wed, 17 Sep 2025 19:12:08 GMT"}, "extraction_method": "rss_with_modern_fallback", "content_type": "article", "word_count": 660, "content_length": 4260, "processing_timestamp": "2025-09-29T05:07:47.106088", "publication_day_of_week": "Wednesday", "publication_month": "September", "publication_year": 2025, "age_days": 11, "threat_keywords": ["apt", "attack", "exploit", "breach", "threat", "security"], "threat_keyword_count": 6, "threat_hunting_score": 4.4, "perfect_keyword_matches": [], "good_keyword_matches": [], "lolbas_matches": [], "intelligence_matches": ["observed", "in the wild", "targeted", "exploited"], "negative_matches": ["blog post"], "processed_at": "2025-09-29T05:07:47.117628"}	3803787110543212118	6	2025-09-29 05:07:47.47562	pending	0	2025-09-29 05:07:47.477646	2025-09-29 05:07:47.477646
527	20	https://www.darkreading.com/vulnerabilities-threats/raven-stealer-scavenges-chrome-data-telegram	Raven Stealer Scavenges Chromium Data Via Telegram	2025-09-17 12:06:52	\N	["Elizabeth Montalbano, Contributing Writer"]	[]	The new lightweight stealer, distributed via underground forums and cracked software, demonstrates an important evolution in the stealth of commodity infostealing malware.	Elizabeth Montalbano, Contributing Writer September 17, 2025 A black raven against the blurred backdrop of a mountainous desert landscape Source: Arto Hakola via Alamy Stock Photo A new lightweight infostealer called Raven is swooping into client environments via underground forums and cracked software to pick off data from Chromium browsers and other applications, with a unique exfiltration method through the Telegram chat app aimed at evading detection. The creators of the so-called Raven Stealer, written primarily in Delphi and C++, developed the malware "for stealth and efficiency," according to researchers from Point Wild's Lat61 Threat Intelligence who discovered the fledgling malware. Raven "operates with minimal user interaction while maintaining a high level of operational concealment" to steal credentials from various applications, they noted. The malware's malicious activities include harvesting cookies, autofill entries, browsing history, and other data from Chromium-based browsers like Google Chrome and Microsoft Edge, as well as stealing credentials from other applications and performing real-time data exfiltration via integration with a Telegram bot, according to a blog post published this week from the Point Wild Lat61 Threat Intelligence team. Because it's lightweight and distributed via underground forums, the stealer represents "a persistent threat to both personal and enterprise environments," Lat61 Threat Intelligence researcher Onkar R. Sonawane wrote in the post. Raven Stealer also demonstrates an evolution in commodity malware in not only its infostealing capabilities but also in how it covers its tracks "through in-memory execution and Telegram exfiltration," observes Zulfikar Ramzan, head of the team and CTO of Point Wild. "It s a reminder that attackers are packaging advanced techniques into tools that even low-skilled actors can use." Attackers promote the stealer via a dedicated Telegram channel, integrating the chat app for command-and-control (C2) operations. The malware also offers a streamlined user interface and support for dynamic modules, which "enhances the tool's appeal within the commodity malware," Sonawane wrote. Details of Raven Stealer's Malware Execution Upon execution, the Raven payload immediately activates a reporting mechanism that aggregates all harvested data including login credentials, system details, and browser-related artifacts into a well-organized format. "This compiled report is structured for seamless transmission to the threat actor, commonly labeled as the 'admin,' enabling remote access and review of the stolen information," according to Sonawane. The primary targets of the stealer are browser-based authentication data, including saved passwords and session cookies, and it accesses local storage paths and credential vaults on Chrome , Brave, and similar browsers to extract this data. "This behavior enables the attacker to harvest sensitive login information for potential account compromise, data exfiltration, or further lateral movement," Sonawane explained. Perhaps one of the most interesting aspects of how Raven operates is how it extricates the data that it steals from applications and browsers, according to Point Wild. "One of its standout features is the use of Telegram for exfiltration, where stolen data such as passwords, browser cookies, and payment information is sent through encrypted messaging channels, bypassing many conventional security filters," Sonawane wrote. Once the stealer consolidates stolen credentials and system information within a well-defined folder hierarchy to streamline access and transmission of collected data, the stealer deposits the extracted browser artifacts into plain text files on a specific location of the victim machine's C drive. It then begins the exfiltration process, first by loading a Telegram Chat ID and Bot Token, then by accessing the AES encryption key stored in the Edge browser s Local State file. "This key is used to decrypt sensitive browser data such as cookies and credentials," Sonawane wrote. The malware saves the decrypted data in plain text format at another C drive location, captures and stores a screenshot of the victim's desktop, compresses all collected artifacts into a zip archive, and then sends it to the attacker via Telegram using an API endpoint. Once Raven completes exfiltration, it reboots into Safe Mode with Networking and uses UltraAV antivirus to delete malicious files, thus eliminating any trace of its malicious activity. How Companies Can Mitigate Stealer Malware The number of infostealers making the rounds to steal sensitive data from client-side browsers is currently at epidemic proportions, even as law-enforcement efforts continue to make headway in disrupting their ranks. Amid the emergence of new stealers such as Raven, attackers continue to spread other, more seasoned infostealing malware such as Lumma , Vidar , Chaes , and others, on a regular basis. These stealers are not only dangerous in and of themselves, but they also act as a gateway drug to further malicious activity, such as the propagation of ransomware, phishing, and other secondary attacks that use stolen credentials and other data extracted by the stealers. To mitigate the impact of Raven and other infostealers, organizations should practice behavioral-based threat detection, vigilantly monitor Telegram traffic, engage in user education on phishing tactics, and consistently patch software to close vulnerabilities, Sonawane recommended. Organizations also should ensure that AV protection is updated and enabled for real-time protection, as well as prevent employees across the organization from downloading pirated or cracked software using the workplace IT environment. This will help shut down common means of distribution for infostealers, he added. About the Author Elizabeth Montalbano, Contributing Writer Elizabeth Montalbano is a freelance writer, journalist, and therapeutic writing mentor with more than 25 years of professional experience. Her areas of expertise include technology, business, and culture. Elizabeth previously lived and worked as a full-time journalist in Phoenix, San Francisco, and New York City; she currently resides in a village on the southwest coast of Portugal. In her free time, she enjoys surfing, hiking with her dogs, traveling, playing music, yoga, and cooking. See more from Elizabeth Montalbano, Contributing Writer You May Also Like	c57e2c965c83464e47fc976ed1c84e5d2641b04c4ac7701ebc3bc17dc5934351	{"feed_entry": {"id": "https://www.darkreading.com/vulnerabilities-threats/raven-stealer-scavenges-chrome-data-telegram", "link": "https://www.darkreading.com/vulnerabilities-threats/raven-stealer-scavenges-chrome-data-telegram", "published": "Wed, 17 Sep 2025 12:06:52 GMT", "updated": "Wed, 17 Sep 2025 12:06:52 GMT"}, "extraction_method": "rss_with_modern_fallback", "content_type": "article", "word_count": 945, "content_length": 6480, "processing_timestamp": "2025-09-29T05:07:47.122217", "publication_day_of_week": "Wednesday", "publication_month": "September", "publication_year": 2025, "age_days": 11, "threat_keywords": ["malware", "ransomware", "phishing", "apt", "attack", "threat", "security"], "threat_keyword_count": 7, "threat_hunting_score": 8.6, "perfect_keyword_matches": [], "good_keyword_matches": ["Monitor", "Detection", "payload"], "lolbas_matches": [], "intelligence_matches": ["threat actor", "compromise", "discovered", "victim", "ransomware"], "negative_matches": ["blog post"], "processed_at": "2025-09-29T05:07:47.138448"}	290