534	20	https://www.darkreading.com/cyber-risk/securityscorecard-buys-ai-automation-capabilities-boosts-vendor-risk-management	SecurityScorecard Buys AI Automation Capabilities, Boosts Vendor Risk Management	2025-09-15 22:09:33	\N	["Fahmida Y. Rashid"]	[]	The company acquired HyperComply to help enterprises automate vendor security reviews and gain a real-time picture of the security of their entire supply chain.	Fahmida Y. Rashid , Managing Editor, Features , Dark Reading September 15, 2025 Source: Yuri Arcurs via Alamy Stock Photo NEWS BRIEF SecurityScorecard purchased Canadian startup HyperComply earlier this month to improve third-party risk assessment by helping vendors respond to vendor assessment questionnaires. HyperComply's security questionnaire automation and compliance management platform helps enterprises assess vendors by automating security questionnaires and responses to requests for proposals. The company, founded in 2019, combines machine learning and artificial intelligence with human verification to ensure answers are accurate, while reducing the amount of work and time needed to complete the questionnaires. Organizations manage their increasingly complex vendor ecosystems with security assessment questionnaires and third-party risk ratings. These assessments are manual and time-consuming for both enterprises and vendors as each review requires detailed responses about compliance frameworks, security controls, and risk management practices, wrote Aleksandr Yampolsky, CEO and co-founder of SecurityScorecard, in a blog post announcing the acquisition. And vendors answer similar questions multiple times for different customers in slightly different formats, making the process both repetitive and time-consuming. "These manual reviews delay business deals and consume valuable expertise that could focus on threat prevention," Yampolsky wrote, noting that sales teams cannot close deals while waiting for security teams to work through the assessments. HyperComply addresses the vendor pain point by automating the process of answering over 92% of questionnaire items by using prevalidated content. The platform also offers tools, such as a knowledge base, workflows, templates, and browser extensions, to speed up the process. Until now, SecurityScorecard's focus has been on helping security teams assess and rate third-party security risks. HyperComply helps vendors being assessed manage their parts of the security assurance process. The combination of SecurityScorecard's ratings data and HyperComply's compliance capabilities will help enterprises onboard vendors faster and streamline due diligence, Yampolsky said. SecurityScorecard plans to offer HyperComply as both a standalone solution and as part of its supply chain risk management platform. This will let customers use the technology purely as a questionnaire automation tool or as part of a broader detection and response workflow. The integrated offerings are expected later this year. Yampolsky also said there are currently no plans to remove or change features that customers rely on. Financial terms of the transaction were not disclosed. Read more about: News Briefs About the Author Fahmida Y. Rashid Managing Editor, Features, Dark Reading As Dark Reading s managing editor for features, Fahmida Y Rashid focuses on stories that provide security professionals with the information they need to do their jobs. She has spent over a decade analyzing news events and demystifying security technology for IT professionals and business managers. Prior to specializing in information security, Fahmida wrote about enterprise IT, especially networking, open source, and core internet infrastructure. Before becoming a journalist, she spent over 10 years as an IT professional -- and has experience as a network administrator, software developer, management consultant, and product manager. Her work has appeared in various business and test trade publications, including VentureBeat, CSO Online, InfoWorld, eWEEK, CRN, PC Magazine, and Tom s Guide. See more from Fahmida Y. Rashid You May Also Like	6c3cc162f5ac2f4c02b32fc517bd6e313ca49ae526febaa023a9cf0c5d9d350e	{"feed_entry": {"id": "https://www.darkreading.com/cyber-risk/securityscorecard-buys-ai-automation-capabilities-boosts-vendor-risk-management", "link": "https://www.darkreading.com/cyber-risk/securityscorecard-buys-ai-automation-capabilities-boosts-vendor-risk-management", "published": "Mon, 15 Sep 2025 22:09:33 GMT", "updated": "Mon, 15 Sep 2025 22:09:33 GMT"}, "extraction_method": "rss_with_modern_fallback", "content_type": "article", "word_count": 520, "content_length": 3693, "processing_timestamp": "2025-09-29T05:07:47.308501", "publication_day_of_week": "Monday", "publication_month": "September", "publication_year": 2025, "age_days": 13, "threat_keywords": ["threat", "security"], "threat_keyword_count": 2, "threat_hunting_score": 0.2, "perfect_keyword_matches": [], "good_keyword_matches": ["Detection", "--", "network"], "lolbas_matches": [], "intelligence_matches": [], "negative_matches": ["read more", "blog post"], "processed_at": "2025-09-29T05:07:47.318402"}	15983529860801576636	12	2025-09-29 05:07:47.507924	pending	0	2025-09-29 05:07:47.509873	2025-09-29 05:07:47.509874
535	20	https://www.darkreading.com/vulnerabilities-threats/hybridpetya-ransomware-bypasses-secure-boot	'HybridPetya' Ransomware Bypasses Secure Boot	2025-09-15 20:59:56	\N	["Jai Vijayan, Contributing Writer"]	[]	The malware, which has traits of Petya ransomware and the infamous NotPetya wiper, is designed to target UEFI-based systems, according to researchers.	Jai Vijayan, Contributing Writer September 15, 2025 Source: WhataWin via Shutterstock Researchers have discovered a new malware strain that combines the destructive capabilities of NotPetya, the recoverable encryption functionality of Petya ransomware, and the ability to bypass Secure Boot protections. The malware targets modern UEFI-based systems through two attack vectors. It can deploy malicious UEFI payloads directly to the EFI System Partition and encrypt the Master File Table (MFT), making all files on the partition inaccessible. Some samples can exploit CVE 2024 7344, a vulnerability in the Howyar Reloader UEFI application that bypasses Secure Boot . HybridPetya Malware Not Deployed Yet ESET, which is tracking the threat as "HybridPetya," discovered samples on VirusTotal recently and said there is no evidence that anyone has actually deployed the malware in the wild yet. But it is now at least the fourth known example of malware that can bypass UEFI Secure Boot, a security feature designed to ensure that only trusted, digitally signed code can run during system startup. "Although HybridPetya is not actively spreading, its technical capabilities especially MFT encryption, UEFI system compatibility, and Secure Boot bypass make it noteworthy for future threat monitoring," ESET security researcher Martin Smol r said in a blog post . The malware "shows that Secure Boot bypasses are not just possible they're becoming more common and attractive to both researchers and attackers." Petya is ransomware that surfaced in 2016 and spread like wildfire on computers around the world. NotPetya is a 2017 variant that first hit systems in Ukraine before causing havoc worldwide. Though it purported to be ransomware, NotPetya was actually a destructive wiper that rendered systems irrecoverable, even in situations where a victim might have paid the demanded ransom. Insurance firms estimated the attacks cost organizations billions of dollars in damages worldwide. HybridPetya is different in that it combines the capabilities of both variants. As with Petya and NotPetya, the new malware gives attackers a way to encrypt the master File Table on New Technology File Systems (NTFS), rendering a computer useless. ESET's analysis also showed HybridPetya filenames and some operational behaviors to be reminiscent of NotPetya. But while HybridPetya mirrors NotPetya s ability to cause significant system disruption, it also allows operators of the malware to reconstruct the victim's decryption key and recover their data, according to the security vendor. The most troubling difference, from a defender standpoint, is HybridPetya's ability to install harmful code directly into a computer's UEFI firmware. That makes the malware hard for security teams to detect. It also allows the malware to persist on a system even if the operating system is reinstalled or the hard drive is wiped. In addition to directly deploying malicious UEFI payloads, some HybridPetya versions include an exploit for CVE 2024 7344 , a vulnerability in the Howyar Reloader UEFI bootloader component. The vulnerability gives attackers a way to load unsigned software during the startup process in such a manner as to bypass the Secure Boot process. Growing Cyber Threats from UEFI Bootkits The emergence of HybridPetya highlights the growing threat to organizations from UEFI bootkits that reside at a computer's startup sequence level rather than at the usual operating system level. There are least three other publicly known examples of similar malware: BlackLotus from 2023, which was the first known instance; Bootkitty, the first bootloader to target Linux systems ; and Hyper-V Backdoor , a proof-of-concept malware that exploited a vulnerable component in a Kaspersky bootloader. Security researchers have warned of such bootkits posing a clear and present danger to organizations, both because of how hard they are to detect and how difficult they are to remove. A rootkit's ability to remain persistent on a compromised device even through operating system and hard drive reinstalls heightens the need to ensure firmware and UEFI are properly updated and patched. CISA has also recommended that security teams audit and manage UEFI components like any other software and continuously collect and analyze UEFI-activity related logs for signs of malicious activity. About the Author Jai Vijayan, Contributing Writer Jai Vijayan is a seasoned technology reporter with over 20 years of experience in IT trade journalism. He was most recently a Senior Editor at Computerworld, where he covered information security and data privacy issues for the publication. Over the course of his 20-year career at Computerworld, Jai also covered a variety of other technology topics, including big data, Hadoop, Internet of Things, e-voting, and data analytics. Prior to Computerworld, Jai covered technology issues for The Economic Times in Bangalore, India. Jai has a Master's degree in Statistics and lives in Naperville, Ill. See more from Jai Vijayan, Contributing Writer You May Also Like	74c710c00e50efe836d5a819f10eebcbd27952f781e31f92a6f5ba5b3361415e	{"feed_entry": {"id": "https://www.darkreading.com/vulnerabilities-threats/hybridpetya-ransomware-bypasses-secure-boot", "link": "https://www.darkreading.com/vulnerabilities-threats/hybridpetya-ransomware-bypasses-secure-boot", "published": "Mon, 15 Sep 2025 20:59:56 GMT", "updated": "Mon, 15 Sep 2025 20:59:56 GMT"}, "extraction_method": "rss_with_modern_fallback", "content_type": "article", "word_count": 776, "content_length": 5078, "processing_timestamp": "2025-09-29T05:07:47.322561", "